<div class='row t20 b1'>
  <div class='medium-4 columns'><b>Preview:</b></div>
  <div class='medium-8 columns'><div class="webex-group">
<div class="webex-question">
<div class="webex-check webex-box">
<p>A firm has the following production function: <span class="math display">\[
F(K,L)= K L^{2}.
\]</span> The price for one unit of <em>capital</em> is <span class="math inline">\(p_K = 13\)</span> and the price for one unit of <em>labor</em> is <span class="math inline">\(p_L = 13\)</span>. Minimize the costs of the firm considering its production function and given a target production output of 430 units.</p>
<p>How high are in this case the minimal costs?</p>
<p><input class='webex-solveme nospaces' data-tol='0.01' size='20' data-answer='["185.44"]'/></p>
</div>
<div class="webex-solution">
<p><em>Step 1</em>: Formulating the minimization problem. <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
\min_{K,L} C(K,L) &amp; = p_K K + p_L L\\
 &amp; = 13 K + 13 L\\
\mbox{subject~to:} &amp;  F(K,L) = Q \\
&amp; K L^{2} = 430 
\end{aligned}
\]</span> <em>Step 2</em>: Lagrange function. <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}(K, L, \lambda) &amp; = C(K, L) - \lambda (F(K, L) - Q) \\
  &amp; = 13 K + 13 L - \lambda (K L^{2} -430)
\end{aligned}
\]</span> <em>Step 3</em>: First order conditions. <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial {\mathcal {L}}}{\partial K} &amp; = 13 - \lambda L^{2} = 0\\
\frac{\partial {\mathcal {L}}}{\partial L} &amp; = 13 - {2} \lambda K L^{2 - 1} = 0 \\
\frac{\partial {\mathcal {L}}}{\partial \lambda} &amp; = -(K L^{2}-430) = 0
\end{aligned}
\]</span> <em>Step 4</em>: Solve the system of equations for <span class="math inline">\(K\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(L\)</span>, and <span class="math inline">\(\lambda\)</span>.</p>
<p>Solving the first two equations for <span class="math inline">\(\lambda\)</span> and equating them gives: <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{13}{L^{2}} &amp; = \frac{13}{2 K L^{2 - 1}}\\
K &amp; = \frac{13}{2 \cdot 13} \cdot L^{2 - (2 - 1)}\\
K &amp; = \frac{13}{26} \cdot L
\end{aligned}
\]</span> Substituting this in the optimization constraint gives: <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
K L^{2} &amp; = 430\\
\left(\frac{13}{26}\cdot L \right) L^{2} &amp; = 430\\
\frac{13}{26} L^{3} &amp; = 430\\
L &amp; = \left(\frac{26}{13} \cdot 430\right)^{\frac{1}{3}} = 9.5096854 \approx 9.51\\
K &amp; = \frac{13}{26} \cdot L = 4.7548427 \approx 4.75
\end{aligned}
\]</span></p>
<p>The minimal costs can be obtained by substituting the optimal factor combination in the objective function: <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
C(K, L) &amp; = 13 K + 13 L\\
        &amp; = 61.812955 + 123.62591 \\
        &amp; = 185.438865 \approx 185.44
\end{aligned}
\]</span></p>
<p>Given the target output, the minimal costs are <span class="math inline">\(185.44\)</span>.<br />
<img src="data:image/png;base64," /></p>
</div>
</div>

\end{aligned}

<div class="webex-question">
<div class="webex-check webex-box">
<p>A firm has the following production function: <span class="math display">\[
F(K,L)= K L^{}.
\]</span> The price for one unit of <em>capital</em> is <span class="math inline">\(p_K = 10\)</span> and the price for one unit of <em>labor</em> is <span class="math inline">\(p_L = 24\)</span>. Minimize the costs of the firm considering its production function and given a target production output of 720 units.</p>
<p>What is the amount of the input factor <em>labor</em> in this minimum?</p>
<p><input class='webex-solveme nospaces' data-tol='0.01' size='20' data-answer='["17.32"]'/></p>
</div>
<div class="webex-solution">
<p><em>Step 1</em>: Formulating the minimization problem. <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
\min_{K,L} C(K,L) &amp; = p_K K + p_L L\\
 &amp; = 10 K + 24 L\\
\mbox{subject~to:} &amp;  F(K,L) = Q \\
&amp; K L^{} = 720 
\end{aligned}
\]</span> <em>Step 2</em>: Lagrange function. <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
\mathcal{L}(K, L, \lambda) &amp; = C(K, L) - \lambda (F(K, L) - Q) \\
  &amp; = 10 K + 24 L - \lambda (K L^{} -720)
\end{aligned}
\]</span> <em>Step 3</em>: First order conditions. <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{\partial {\mathcal {L}}}{\partial K} &amp; = 10 - \lambda L^{} = 0\\
\frac{\partial {\mathcal {L}}}{\partial L} &amp; = 24 - {1} \lambda K L^{1 - 1} = 0 \\
\frac{\partial {\mathcal {L}}}{\partial \lambda} &amp; = -(K L^{}-720) = 0
\end{aligned}
\]</span> <em>Step 4</em>: Solve the system of equations for <span class="math inline">\(K\)</span>, <span class="math inline">\(L\)</span>, and <span class="math inline">\(\lambda\)</span>.</p>
<p>Solving the first two equations for <span class="math inline">\(\lambda\)</span> and equating them gives: <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
\frac{10}{L^{}} &amp; = \frac{24}{1 K L^{1 - 1}}\\
K &amp; = \frac{24}{1 \cdot 10} \cdot L^{1 - (1 - 1)}\\
K &amp; = \frac{24}{10} \cdot L
\end{aligned}
\]</span> Substituting this in the optimization constraint gives: <span class="math display">\[
\begin{aligned}
K L^{} &amp; = 720\\
\left(\frac{24}{10}\cdot L \right) L^{} &amp; = 720\\
\frac{24}{10} L^{2} &amp; = 720\\
L &amp; = \left(\frac{10}{24} \cdot 720\right)^{\frac{1}{2}} = 17.3205081 \approx 17.32\\
K &amp; = \frac{24}{10} \cdot L = 41.5692194 \approx 41.57
\end{aligned}
\]</span> <!--

<div class='row t20 b1'>
  <div class='medium-4 columns'><b>Description:</b></div>
  <div class='medium-8 columns'>Computing the solution to a cost minimization problem subject to an output constraint where the production fuction with arguments capital and labor is of Cobb-Douglas type. As  <code class="highlighter-rouge">num</code> exercises have only a single numeric solution (and to make test takers read the exercise carefully), one of three natural quantities in the optimum is selected randomly as the question: the first argument (capital), the second argument (labor), or the minimal function value (costs). The optimal solution is also displayed graphically using a contour plot.</div>
</div>
